displayTitle: Top tips for dressing a tree
title: Text Title

_items.title: STEP 1: FLUFF THE BRANCHES
_items.body:
Spend a good amount of time putting your tree together and fluffing the branches to give it that full and authentic look. It's all in the preparation. If you've fluffed your tree and the lights are even, you can't go wrong. 


Simple.


To fluff each branch, separate each of the tips and splay them wide – this will ensure no gaps are left in the tree which hides all the lights' wires and makes it easier to hang decorations on.  


Handy Tip: This is the most important step of setting up a tree so don’t skimp on this step. Even the most beautifully decorated tree will look sad and spindly if it's uneven and has multiple gaps.

Make sure you spend a good half an hour or so getting your Christmas lights positioned just right. Start from the top and work your way down, weaving them around every major branch moving from the trunk to the tip and back. Try to hide as much of the wiring as possible.


Handy tip: Plug the lights before starting work. This way you can see whether they are even as you position them and you wont be caught out by faulty lights at the end.
_items.title: STEP 2: PUT ON THE LIGHTS

_items.body:
Either beads, ribbon or foil, garlands add texture and interest to your tree. Again, start from the top and work your way round, trying to keep it as even as possible. You may need to rearrange some of the tips to achieve this.


Handy Tip: It's best to do this before the baubles and other decorations, so you don't knock them off while you work.
_items.title: STEP 3: PUT ON THE GARLANDS
STEP 4: ADD THE DECORATIONS
_items.body:
When hanging baubles, start from the inside of your tree and work out. Start with plain-coloured baubles as a base (basic multipack baubles are ideal), adding in more decorative, expensive baubles later. 


Hang the biggest ornaments deeper into the tree to give it depth, and smaller ones on the ends of branches. Similarly, use smaller decorations towards the top of the tree and larger ones down below. Space them evenly and use a variety of shapes, sizes and materials.


If you find a bauble that you like, buy it in multiples because it will give your tree balance. Finish off with statement pieces like clip on flowers or birds.


Handy Tip: Move expensive, glass baubles to the top  - you know what will happen to them otherwise.

_items.title: STEP 5: ADD THE FINISHING TOUCHES
_items.body:
Cover the base of your tree with a tree skirt. Tree skirts hide wires and the tree look much cleaner and tidier. Finish with an eye catching Christmas tree topper – stars and angels are always popular, while snowflakes and peacocks are on trend.


Handy Tip: Beware of toppers that are heavy - they will have to sit on the flimsiest part of your tree for several weeks so make sure your topper isn't in danger of toppling.

_items.title: STORE TEAM MEMBERS

_items.body:
Suggesting themes, and talking about how to choose/buy decorations.


Can I share with you some tips on how to decorate your tree?


I like to treat myself to a few new decorations each year. Because we have a range of themes, I can easily find decorations that fit with my style.


We’ve started a new tradition in our family. Each year we get each other a new Christmas decoration for the tree. 


There are some really fun decorations this year that I’ve got in mind for my grandchildren.
_items.title: CHRISTMAS TRIM TEAM MEMBERS

_items.body:
Myer Christmas plush characters


Have you seen the animated characters in the last two years' Myer Christmas campaigns? 


Elf, Reindeer, Angel and Mouse are back again this year to save Christmas, and now they're available as plush items you can put under your tree!


Spirit of Christmas CD (available in October)


Have you thought about some Christmas music?

 

This year is the 24th anniversary of the Spirit of Christmas CD. We’ve put together the best of the best, including Guy Sebastian, Paul Kelly, Jessica Mauboy and The Wiggles. There's something in there for everyone!


It’s also a wonderful gift idea, especially as all the proceeds go to The Salvation Army.
